HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 228
BY REPRESENTATIVE SCHLEGEL
A RESOLUTION
To designate Tuesday, May 5, 2026, as Literacy Day at the Louisiana State Capitol and to
recognize the Center for Literacy & Learning for its leadership in advancing literacy
statewide.
WHEREAS, students who do not read proficiently by the end of third grade are four
times more likely to drop out of school, and those who lack basic reading proficiency are
nearly six times more likely to leave school without earning a diploma; and
WHEREAS, dyslexia is a learning disability that affects as many as one in five
individuals and presents a significant barrier to reading success without proper support; and
WHEREAS, literacy is foundational to a student's academic success, long-term
opportunity, and personal empowerment; and
WHEREAS, in 2022, seventy-two percent of Louisiana fourth grade students did not
read proficiently, and the state placed forty-second in the nation for fourth grade reading
achievement; and
WHEREAS, in 2024, Louisiana made historic progress by climbing twenty-six
places in national rankings to now rank sixteenth in the nation for fourth grade reading,
according to the National Assessment of Educational Progress; and
WHEREAS, the Center for Literacy & Learning was founded in 1992 and has spent
thirty-four years implementing evidence-based instructional and coaching practices that
improve teaching and increase student learning outcomes from birth to twelfth grade; and
WHEREAS, the Center for Literacy & Learning draws on over three hundred fifty
combined years of professional education experience to focus on closing the achievement
gap through targeted, high-quality professional development for educators of at-risk
students; and
